\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {13.1}{\ignorespaces Evolution of the entropy defect $\mathcal  {D}(t)$ through the three operational modes. In Mode~1 (blue), defect stays near zero: the dynamics remain close to $\Fix  (\eta )$. In Mode~2 (orange, crucible), defect rises above $D_c$ as the Refuse-induced entropy production drives configurations away from canonical representatives while mutual information retention keeps the system from fragmenting. In Mode~3 (red), defect saturates toward $D_{\max }$ as coherence retention fails. Return to Mode~1 (rightmost blue region) occurs when entropy production falls below $\sigma _c$, driving defect back toward zero. The monotonicity theorem (\cref  {thm:D-monotone}) governs the rising portions of this curve under ergodic mixing conditions.}}{41}{figure.13.1}\protected@file@percent }
